{"serial": "09045", "department_serial": 3, "code": "GS4451", "class": "*", "name": {"en": "An Introduction to Modern Astronomy", "ch": "現代天文學簡介"}, "notice": {"en": "", "ch": "已修習CC0203(天文學導論)、CC0212(神秘的宇宙)不得修習本課程；本課程為全英語授課。"}, "instructor": {"en": ["Kinoshita Daisuke"], "ch": ["木下大輔"]}, "credits": 2, "time_loc": [{"time": {"week": 1, "session": ["A", "B"]}, "loc": {"building": "A", "room": "106"}}], "isRequired": false, "isFullSem": false, "MaxStu": 50, "department": {"ch": "通識教育中心", "en": "General Education Center"}, "system": {"ch": "學士班", "en": "Undergraduate Programme"}, "language": {"ch": "英語", "en": "English"}, "card": {"ch": "部份使用", "en": "Optional"}, "assigned": 13, "selected": 50, "remark": {"ch": "已修習CC0203(天文學導論)、CC0212(神秘的宇宙)不得修習本課程；本課程為全英語授課。", "en": ""}, "goal": {"ch": "This course provides an opportunity for undergraduate students to study\nintroductory astronomy in English. It is mainly for (1) foreign\nstudents who is not yet fluent in Chinese and is willing to study\nastronomy, and (2) local Taiwanese students who is willing to study\nastronomy in English. The goals of this course include, but not limited\nto,\n(a) knowing properties of various types of celestial objects and understanding underlying physics behind them,\n(b) knowing astronomical phenomena and understanding underlying physics behind them,\n(c) knowing astronomical techniques and understanding underlying physics behind them.\nThis course tries to describe astronomical objects and their\nproperties / phenomena / related observational techniques using high\nschool level mathematics and physics. Each week, one simple and\nfundamental question is raised, and the lecture is given to answer the\nquestion.", "en": "This course provides an opportunity for undergraduate students to study\nintroductory astronomy in English. It is mainly for (1) foreign\nstudents who is not yet fluent in Chinese and is willing to study\nastronomy, and (2) local Taiwanese students who is willing to study\nastronomy in English. The goals of this course include, but not limited\nto,\n(a) knowing properties of various types of celestial objects and understanding underlying physics behind them,\n(b) knowing astronomical phenomena and understanding underlying physics behind them,\n(c) knowing astronomical techniques and understanding underlying physics behind them.\nThis course tries to describe astronomical objects and their\nproperties / phenomena / related observational techniques using high\nschool level mathematics and physics. Each week, one simple and\nfundamental question is raised, and the lecture is given to answer the\nquestion."}, "outline": {"ch": "Topics for this course include following.\n1. How long is one day, one month, and one year?\n2. How to record electromagnetic radiation from celestial objects?\n3. How to measure the distance to a celestial object?\n4. How to measure the temperature of a celestial object?\n5. How to measure the size of a celestial object?\n6. How to measure the mass of a celestial object?\n7. Why the Earth has its own atmosphere, but the Moon does not?\n8. What is the energy source of a star?\n9. How were many different elements created?\n10. How to know the internal structure of a celestial object?\n11. How to find an Earth-like planet outside of our solar system?\n12. How to know the size and mass of the Milky Way Galaxy?\n13. How to know the age of our solar system?\n14. How to know the age of a star?\n15. How to know the age of the Universe?\n16. What can we learn from latest images obtained by new telescopes?", "en": "Topics for this course include following.\n1. How long is one day, one month, and one year?\n2. How to record electromagnetic radiation from celestial objects?\n3. How to measure the distance to a celestial object?\n4. How to measure the temperature of a celestial object?\n5. How to measure the size of a celestial object?\n6. How to measure the mass of a celestial object?\n7. Why the Earth has its own atmosphere, but 